      \field{labelnamesource}{author}
      \field{labeltitlesource}{title}
      \field{abstract}{Our study investigates whether the use of Large Language Models (LLMs) for writing assistance systematically distorts how others perceive LLM users and the opinions they express. The study employs a two-phase design: In Phase 1 (Writing), participants ("writers'') report their demographic characteristics and then respond to political propositions by providing numeric stance ratings, opinion bullet points and opinion paragraphs. Writers also report their emotional states while writing, their issue knowledge and how important each issue is to them. For each proposition, each writer is then randomly assigned to one of three LLMs, which generates a version of the writer's opinion paragraph based on one of three randomly assigned input conditions. Writers can edit these AI-generated paragraphs and select which version they prefer for communicating their views. In Phase 2 (Rating), participants ("raters''), who are distinct from the Phase 1 writers, evaluate the paragraphs produced in Phase 1, without knowing the provenance of the paragraphs. Raters assess paragraph attributes (e.g. originality), make inferences about writer attributes (e.g. issue knowledge), writer personality traits (e.g. optimism), as well as writer demographics and emotional states. This design allows for measuring systematic differences in how human-written versus AI-assisted content is perceived, quantifying potential distortive effects of LLM writing assistance.}
      \field{eprinttype}{OSF Registries}
      \field{title}{Quantifying the {{Distortive Impacts}} of {{LLM Writing Assistance}}}
